  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Secluded Dwelling
  author: Seok Won-gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I make my nest beyond the dust of worldly cares,
    wandering freely through crimson forests and jade-green groves.
    The pine-lined corridor grows ever quieter with spring,
    while the bamboo gate stays closed even in daylight.
    With eaves cut short, the moon arrives unobstructed,
    and the low wall cannot hide the distant mountains.
    After rain, the creek rushes urgent with new life,
    yet when wind ceases, the ridge clouds drift in leisured peace.
    Deep in the ravine, deer crouch in stillness,
    and birds return of their own will to the dense woods.
    Thus I pass from dawn to dusk in unhurried ease,
    cultivating the simple freedom of an ungoverned heart.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is attributed to Seok Won-gam (釋圓鑑), a Buddhist monk-poet of medieval Korea, suggesting this dwelling may be a temple hermitage or monastic retreat.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'low wall' and 'short eaves' are not defects but deliberate choices that keep the dwelling open to nature's presence—moon, mountains, clouds, and wildlife.
  - key: ''
    value: The closing reference to 'an ungoverned heart' (疏頑) reflects Buddhist ideals of simplicity and detachment from worldly concerns.
